DePIN

DePIN Summit 2024

Dylan Bane
Seth Bloomberg

Aug 13, 2024 ⋅  8 min read

On August 10th, the top DePIN builders and investors from around the world gathered in NYC for the 2nd annual DePIN Summit.

The Summit took place amid immense growth in the DePIN sector over the last year, with the total DePIN market cap up 400% to $20 billion YoY and fundraising volume up 296% so far in 2024 compared to last year.

Overlooking the Hudson River on a crystal clear summer day, attendees shared their visions for DePIN and excitement for one of the fastest-growing spaces in crypto. Conversations ranged from GPU compute networks powering the growth in AI to decentralized 3D printing to updating the energy grid with virtual power plants.

Messari was lucky enough to have both current analysts and alumni in attendance, giving presentations, and moderating panel discussions.

So what did our analysts takeaway from the Summit?

Dylan

What immediately stuck out was the diversity of projects building in the space and the real-world problems that these projects are solving. Fixing outdated energy grids built in 1898 with Virtual Power Plants, using “vampire attacks” on Doordash to build a decentralized Uber with zk-TLS, making at-home internet virtually free for households through decentralized broadband, among a wide variety of other problems being tackled. These are the real-world use cases that the industry promised would emerge for over a decade now. You can actually explain these projects to your grandma, and she might just understand what the problem being solved is even if the underlying technology is incomprehensible.

A key high-level observation is the lack of real competition between most early-stage projects in DePIN. There are simply too many problems to solve through DePIN to bother with competing with other world-class entrepreneurs in the same vertical. While certain verticals like DeGEN and GPU compute certainly have competitors within their spaces, the markets are so large and the approaches vary to such a degree that competing for market share is a bottom-tier priority at this point. This is a stark contrast to the DeFi and Infrastructure sectors where competition is becoming increasingly intense and innovation is stalling. In DeFi, we’re seeing the space consolidate around intents and sophisticated AMMs, while cheap block space and fast transaction times are nearly commodities at the L1 and L2 levels. There is a decreasing opportunity to build in these sectors compared to DePIN, reflecting the maturation of these markets.

The summit steered towards early-stage protocols, with Bittensor and Helium being the largest DePIN protocols with representation. This worked in the conference’s favor, bringing excitement and energy, with key innovations and new ideas highlighted rather than reflections and assessments of the progress of more established protocols like Filecoin or Akash. Still, problems facing the DePIN sector more broadly were addressed. Overcoming demand-side constraints, resolving long-standing tokenomic inefficiencies, providing essential cyber-security, and even what should be categorized as a DePIN project received ample attention. The panels and presentations were as comprehensive in covering the major problems in DePIN as a 1-day summit could be.

The trends that were most interesting at the DePIN Summit were Decentralized Generative Energy (DeGEN) and Decentralized Wireless (DeWi).

DeGEN

DeGEN was well represented at the conference, with the teams from Daylight Energy, Glow, Srcful, Arkreen, Starpower Energy, and more making an appearance. As mentioned in last week’s DePIN Update, existing energy grids are centralized, outdated, and in need of serious infrastructure investment. With a global transition towards clean energy sources like solar and wind power that are dispersed and decentralized in energy generation, serious modifications to the grid are needed. DeGEN protocols are tackling this issue among others through virtual power plants (VPPs) and other crypto-economic solutions. The approaches varied from Srcful’s proposal to leverage Helium’s hotspots to create an Energy Subnet to Daylight building a protocol to enable a network of VPPs. Most of these projects are still early-stage, but some have already demonstrated remarkable progress. Both Glow and Daylight are on track to exceeding 7-figure ARRs in the next year, Starpower has over 7,000 devices connected to its network, and Srcful’s Energy subnet on Helium seems set for approval. The question is whether DeGEN can continue the momentum into 2025, meeting high expectations for future growth.

DeWi

DeWi was also well represented, with representation from Helium, Andrena/Dawn, WiFi Map, and Oxio, among others.

The hype for Helium was considerable following a near 50% gain in its token over the course of July, the best-performing asset in the top 100 crypto tokens by market cap. The performance seems to be based on Helium Mobile surpassing 100,000 subscribers in July, reaching a large milestone only eight months after its launch in December. The service offers WiFi for $20/month, compared to a national average of $140/month.

Dawn also made an appearance on the main stage, fresh off an $18 million raise announcement to launch a decentralized broadband network for last-mile connectivity. The protocol already signed up 100,000 users within 5 days of its announcement for a Chrome browser extension which allows users to act as Proof-of-Bandwidth validators for the network. Dawn pitches itself as doing for internet connectivity what solar panels did for electricity. Households can acquire infrastructure from Dawn which enables them to provide their own internet connectivity and sell excess supply to a communal network. The cost of an internet connection mostly lies in infrastructure rather than bandwidth. Dawn estimates that the payback period for its infrastructure could be under one year and that profit margins could be over 90% for users.

Built by Andrena, a broadband internet company that acquires wholesale internet bandwidth at a discount and passes on savings to retail users, Dawn has virtually no competition in the decentralized broadband space. It’s up to the team to develop a protocol with sound tokenomics, a properly incentivized supply side, and a robust demand side to potentially reshape the internet market. Should Andrena and Dawn succeed, the protocol stands to become one of the largest crypto projects based on fundamentals.

Seth

DePIN is definitively back. As Dylan noted, the summit itself was very well put together, with the overall size of the event reaching ~3x that of the previous year.

The attendees included a good mix of VCs—some primarily DePIN-focused, like EV3, and some even from the Web2 world—and a wide variety of builders. The DePIN category also seems to be ever-expanding, as DePIN perps projects like Ostium are now present. Even though it may generate some semantics debate, generally, the growing range of what may be considered “DePIN” projects provides positive validation for the overall DePIN sector.

The DePIN sector's appeal stems from its being rooted in “real world” applications with well-understood markets. As Dylan notes, this is further reflected in the excitement around DeGEN and DeWi projects, which have large mature markets with established incumbents (primed for disruption). On the other hand, for example, memecoins are nebulous — are they lottery tickets, the future of work, or something else? Projects like the Helium Mobile 5G network have a clear, tangible purpose – enable anyone to act as a service provider for anyone needing wireless cell service.

Many of the speakers recurringly discussed the bootstrapping of these networks. For many projects, especially ones where the geographical disbursement of physical devices is paramount, the network's supply side must reach a certain capacity level before the demand side can begin tapping into it. For example, decentralized cloud projects are generally location-independent from the perspective of the demand side of the network, whereas “decentralized Uber” and wireless networks heavily rely on creating a stable, healthy supply of providers in very specific geographic locations. The usefulness of the latter networks is, therefore, a function of reaching a critical mass of supply. With this in mind, these projects typically reward, effectively subsidizing, the network's supply side with tokens.

However, solely subsidizing a network’s supply-side often leads to a “build it, and they will come” mindset. While it’s still early for many DePIN projects, their revenues are generally dislocated from their valuations and the value of the token subsidies emitted to supply-side participants. Shayon from Multicoin spoke at the summit and largely attempted to lay out strategies for inducing demand-side growth. Two of the main points were to effectively hire sales and business development teams and, potentially, for smaller-scale work, clearly define bounties that anyone can pick up and execute remotely. It may sound simple, but convincing sales forces, or even businesses, to build on top of a new, decentralized network is no small feat. In both cases, those who successfully drive demand should be rewarded with the project's native token.

While I did not hear it discussed too much on the stage, my final takeaway is that clever token design and issuance mechanics remain front and center for many DePIN projects. Hivemapper provides a great example here: they can incentivize mapping specific, previously unmapped locations and ensure certain geographies always have fresh mapping data. The token mechanism design challenge is not unique to DePIN, but given DePIN’s nearly ubiquitous usage of tokens to bootstrap its protocols, it will certainly have to continue innovating in this area. To this end, some of the newer projects in both the DeGEN and DeWi categories may look to explore the Medallion token model.

About the authors

Dylan Bane

Dylan is an Enterprise Research Analyst focusing on infrastructure, DePIN, and RWAs. Prior to Messari, Dylan worked as an Analyst on the Digital Assets team at T. Rowe Price and in Crypto Venture Capital. Dylan graduated from Princeton University where he co-founded the Princeton Blockchain Club.

Seth Bloomberg

Prior to joining Messari, Seth worked in traditional finance software and services, and has a MSc in Applied Mathematics. Seth is a Senior Research Analyst on the Enterprise Research team, and focuses on infrastructure, verifiable compute, and the AI x Crypto intersection.
